# A Cumulative-Stiffness Horizon Description of Galactic Rotation Curves

Author: Martin Ollett
Year: 2026


------------------------------------------------------------
ABSTRACT
------------------------------------------------------------

We investigate galactic rotation curves using a cumulative-stiffness
framework motivated by Motion–TimeSpace (MTS). In this approach the
relevant structural quantity is not an added halo profile, but the
cumulative radial loading of a baryonic stiffness field.

Across a resolved SPARC sample, rotation curves collapse onto a
universal mastercurve when written in scaled variables

    x = r / R_s
    y = V / V_inf

The characteristic turnover radius R_s is then found to obey a
cumulative horizon law governed by the baryonic stiffness budget.

The leading empirical result is that the turnover condition is well
described by

    S(R_s) = f_h0 S_tot exp[a (μ_S − μ_S0)]

where

    S(r)   = ∫ m(s) ds
    S_tot  = S(r_max)
    μ_S    = d ln S / d ln r

measured near the turnover region.

The data support characteristic values

    f_h0 ≈ 0.16–0.20
    a    ≈ −0.6

The coefficient a is not inserted ad hoc. It follows from the measured
stiffness span across the turnover band of the mastercurve

    0.67 R_s  ≲  r  ≲  1.5 R_s

giving

    a ≈ − Δ ln S_turn / μ_S0

The horizon fraction f_h0 is also naturally linked to the exponential
turnover structure of the mastercurve, corresponding to the
unsaturated fraction

    exp(−z*)

with

    z* ≈ 1.6–1.8

which yields

    f_h0 ≈ 0.16–0.20.

These results support the interpretation that galactic turnover radii
behave as cumulative-stiffness horizons set by baryonic structure.


------------------------------------------------------------
1. INTRODUCTION
------------------------------------------------------------

Standard interpretations of galaxy rotation curves introduce a dark
matter halo whose structural parameters are adjusted to reproduce the
observed velocity profile.

An alternative possibility is that the organizing variable is the
cumulative baryonic structure itself.

The working hypothesis explored here is that galaxies admit a
cumulative-stiffness description: baryonic structure loads an
effective stiffness field and the observed turnover radius corresponds
to a horizon in the accumulated stiffness rather than a separate halo
component.

The central task is therefore to identify the structural law that
determines the turnover scale R_s.


------------------------------------------------------------
2. BARYONIC STIFFNESS FIELD
------------------------------------------------------------

We define a baryonic stiffness kernel

    m(r) = V_b(r) / (r + r_c)^α

where the baryonic velocity contribution is

    V_b²(r) =
        V_gas²(r)
      + V_disk²(r)
      + V_bulge²(r)

The cumulative stiffness profile is

    S(r) = ∫_0^r m(s) ds

and the total stiffness budget

    S_tot = S(r_max)

This construction uses only observed baryonic structure and produces a
monotonic cumulative field.


------------------------------------------------------------
3. UNIVERSAL ROTATION-CURVE MASTERCURVE
------------------------------------------------------------

Across the resolved sample rotation curves collapse when expressed in
normalized variables

    x = r / R_s
    y = V(r) / V_inf

The universal shape is well described by

    y(x) = 1 − exp[ − (x / x0)^ν ]

with fitted parameters approximately

    x0 ≈ 0.97
    ν  ≈ 0.94

This mastercurve provides the operational definition of the turnover
scale R_s.


------------------------------------------------------------
4. FIXED-FRACTION HORIZON TEST
------------------------------------------------------------

A natural first test is whether the turnover occurs at a fixed
fraction of the total cumulative stiffness budget

    S(R_s) = f S_tot

Across the resolved sample

    S(R_s) / S_tot

clusters around

    f_h0 ≈ 0.16

However the fraction is not perfectly constant. Residuals correlate
with both the total stiffness scale and the local stiffness slope.

This indicates that the fixed-fraction law is only the leading
approximation but that R_s still behaves as a cumulative horizon of
the baryonic stiffness field.


------------------------------------------------------------
5. LOCAL STIFFNESS SLOPE
------------------------------------------------------------

Define the logarithmic slope of the cumulative stiffness field

    μ_S = d ln S / d ln r

measured near the turnover region.

Empirically residuals from the fixed-fraction model correlate with
μ_S, indicating that the horizon location depends not only on the
total stiffness budget but also on the rate at which stiffness
accumulates near the turnover.


------------------------------------------------------------
6. TWO-VARIABLE HORIZON LAW
------------------------------------------------------------

The resolved sample is well described by

    S(R_s) = f_h0 S_tot exp[a (μ_S − μ_S0)]

where μ_S0 is the median slope of the sample.

Typical values are

    μ_S0 ≈ 1.32–1.40
    a    ≈ −0.6

This correction removes the residual bias with μ_S and significantly
improves prediction of the turnover radius.


------------------------------------------------------------
7. TURNOVER-WIDTH ORIGIN OF a
------------------------------------------------------------

Near the turnover radius the cumulative field may be written locally

    S(r) ≈ S(R_s) (r / R_s)^μ_S

A change in μ_S alters the rate at which the cumulative field reaches
the same horizon level.

Requiring the same geometric turnover state yields the first-order
correction

    a ≈ − Δ ln S_turn / μ_S0

where Δ ln S_turn is the cumulative stiffness span across the active
turnover zone.

The turnover-width scan identifies the effective window

    0.67 R_s  ≲  r  ≲  1.5 R_s

Across this window

    Δ ln S_turn ≈ 0.87
    μ_S0        ≈ 1.32

giving

    a_pred ≈ −0.66

consistent with the fitted value

    a ≈ −0.60


------------------------------------------------------------
8. ORIGIN OF THE HORIZON FRACTION
------------------------------------------------------------

The mastercurve

    y = 1 − exp(−z)

implies that the unsaturated remainder is

    1 − y = exp(−z)

At the upper end of the active turnover region

    z* ≈ 1.6–1.8

so

    exp(−z*) ≈ 0.16–0.20

This matches the observed cumulative horizon fraction

    S(R_s) / S_tot ≈ 0.16–0.20

Thus the stiffness horizon fraction naturally reflects the exponential
turnover structure of the universal rotation-curve mastercurve.


------------------------------------------------------------
9. PREDICTIVE INTERPRETATION
------------------------------------------------------------

The current structural interpretation is:

1. Galaxies possess a cumulative baryonic stiffness field S(r).
2. The turnover radius occurs when this field reaches a horizon level.
3. The horizon level is a fraction of the total stiffness budget.
4. The fraction is modulated by the local stiffness slope μ_S.
5. The modulation amplitude follows from the turnover width of the
   universal mastercurve.

The resulting structural law is

    S(R_s) = f_h0 S_tot exp[a (μ_S − μ_S0)]

with

    f_h0 ≈ 0.16–0.20
    a    ≈ −0.6


